"PARTITION A  \nSEALED / READ-ONLY  \nINTEGRITY VERIFIED\n\nPARTITION B  \nINCIDENT PACKAGE SEALED  \nWSS-4 CONTROLLER SEAL PRESENT\n\n“Removal time?” Marcus asked.\n\n“Seal at seven-ten-oh-eight,” Elias said. “Media clear four seconds later.”\n\nMarcus opened the custody log over the folder and wrote the time, place, module serial, and Elias’s continuing physical custody. His hand shook. The letters remained legible.\n\n“Partition A?”\n\n“Unchanged.”\n\n“Read the exact display.”\n\nElias did. Marcus recorded every word.\n\nThe radio anchor announced Sterling’s second statement.\n\n“This morning’s attempted penetration of a Washington national-security organization confirms the seriousness of the continuing security emergency. The individuals sought in connection with the sabotage at Apex Building Three have now targeted sensitive communications supporting the United States and its partners.”\n\nThe statement used the real breach to reverse the reason for it.\n\nSterling did not mention Northbridge’s role, the K-17 session, or the signer.\n\n“Law enforcement is coordinating an appropriate federal response. I urge the public to remain calm and permit trained professionals to secure the material at risk.”\n\nThe broadcast cut to Apex footage: Julie at the recovery console, Elias at a restricted terminal, Marcus blocking security, white suppression discharge, the aluminum case leaving through the loading dock.\n\nEvery image was genuine.\n\nTheir order created the lie.\n\nSterling returned.\n\n“I will proceed to the emergency national-security briefing at the Hartwell Executive Briefing Annex as scheduled. The evolving border threat demands institutional discipline, reliable intelligence, and unified action.”\n\nThe dashboard clock showed 07:18.\n\nElias turned the module toward the front.\n\n“The next authentication is seven-forty-six to seven-forty-eight-thirty. Hartwell local perimeter challenge.”\n\nMarcus stopped writing. “The same device has to answer inside the briefing security domain.”\n\n“SSO-NS-zero-zero-four,” Elias said. “Same serial that answered Northbridge.”\n\n“What does the K-seventeen record give us?”\n\n“Tariq’s registered command authority was accepted. Security Line One had been passed. Relay access was not confirmed. Phase B was waiting for authorization.”\n\n“So the relay is not taken.”\n\n“The record does not prove it is.”\n\n“Second masking window?”\n\n“Seven-forty-eight to seven-fifty-four. Source-reconstruction profile pending. The command blocks are still encrypted.”\n\nMarcus closed the log.\n\n“A Sterling-office device authenticated a K-seventeen operational session and is expected inside Hartwell.”\n\n“Yes,” Julie said.\n\n“And we still cannot identify who carried it.”\n\n“No.”\n\nThat was the missing fact.\n\nAn aide could hold it. Counsel. Legislative security. A Northbridge intermediary. Sterling himself.\n\nThe certificate had named an office and a device. It had not shown a hand.\n\nA traffic bulletin interrupted the statement.\n\n“Restrictions are beginning around the Hartwell Executive Briefing Annex. Senator Sterling’s motorcade is moving east through central Washington.”\n\nTwo police motorcycles entered the intersection ahead and stopped cross traffic. Black vehicles approached from the north beneath controlled signals.\n\nThe first SUV passed.\n\nThen the armored sedan.\n\nJulie could not see Sterling through the dark glass. She could not see the signer.\n\nShe could see the route.\n\nPCF-27 waited at the red light while the motorcade crossed. The service radio transmitted the updated Fenwick alert. District units now had the van, the plate, its direction, and confirmation that Julie and Elias had escaped with electronic media.\n\nMarcus watched the last vehicle pass.\n\n“Hartwell will be locked down before we reach it. Your face is on every screen. The van is confirmed. We are wounded, uncredentialed, and every officer around that briefing has been told you attacked two national-security facilities.”\n\nJulie watched the motorcade move toward the next authentication point.\n\n“Then impossible is where he’ll feel safest.”\n\n---\n\n# Chapter 13 - The Carrier Stream\n\nDowntown Washington  \n07:18 Eastern Daylight Time\n\nThe last vehicle in Sterling’s motorcade did not follow the armored sedan.\n\nIt cleared the intersection behind two black sport-utility vehicles, held the broad federal avenue for half a block, then moved right without the police motorcycles. No flags. No visible seal. One rear running light burned weaker than the other.\n\nJulie watched it through the windshield while cross traffic remained stopped.\n\n“Support vehicle,” Marcus said.\n\n“Or staff,” Elias replied from the cargo floor.\n\n“Or nothing connected to the signer,” Julie said.\n\nThe weakened rear light disappeared behind a city bus.\n\nAhead, the rest of the motorcade continued beneath controlled signals toward Hartwell. The police motorcycles opened the intersection one lane at a time. A delivery truck moved first. Then a taxi. PCF-27 waited beneath the red light with its known Virginia plate, white Potomac Critical Facilities markings, and three people the city had been told were armed.\n\nThe service radio transmitted the Fenwick update again.\n\n“District units, suspect contractor van confirmed leaving the L Street response area eastbound. Electronic media believed inside. Coordinate with Hartwell traffic restrictions and do not approach without support.”\n\nThe light changed.\n\nJulie put the van in motion.\n\nHer left hand held the wheel high. The turn pulled against her braced right wrist where her forearm pressed the lower spoke. Pain moved from the base of her thumb into the elbow and stayed there.\n\nMarcus unfolded the road map across his left thigh. Blood had dried to his jaw, but a fresh line had reached the edge of his collar from the reopened scalp wound. The aluminum case stood between his boots. He kept one ankle against it whenever the van changed lanes.\n\nElias held the incident module in both hands. The administrator-token board remained inside the padded sleeve beneath his torn shirt. Without the borrowed rain shell, he looked less like a technician than a man who had slept in his clothes and been dragged through machinery.\n\n“What exactly are we following?” Marcus asked.\n\n“Not Sterling,” Julie said. “The physical path.”\n\n“To Hartwell.”\n\n“To the local challenge.”\n\nElias looked at the module. “The same signer serial has to answer from inside the briefing security domain between seven-forty-six and seven-forty-eight-thirty.”\n\n“We know.”\n\n“We know the device has to be inside. We do not know when it enters.”\n\nMarcus looked through the windshield toward the avenue where the motorcade had vanished. “It may already be there.”\n\n“Yes.”\n\n“Then this is over before it starts.”\n\n“No.” Julie changed lanes behind a municipal utility truck. “If the device went in with the principal motorcade, we identify that route and preserve the limit. If it enters with staff, support, counsel, or a courier, we identify that route. We do not pick the answer before the evidence.”\n\nThe map shook once in Marcus’s hand. He flattened it against his thigh.\n\n“And the van?”\n\n“We get it out of the immediate plate stream.”\n\n“How?”\n\n“We find a place with more than one exit and a view.”\n\n“That is not a place.”\n\n“It is the requirement.”\n\nThe service radio carried a Hartwell traffic advisory. Two approaches were closing to ordinary vehicles. One commercial street remained open west of the federal block, with access restricted at the next avenue.\n\nMarcus traced the street with one finger.\n\n“There is a public garage west of the annex district. Seven levels if they have not rebuilt it. Office parking, early contractors, two vehicle exits.”\n\n“View?”\n\n“Upper levels face east.”\n\n“Distance?”\n\n“Two blocks from the outer Hartwell approaches. Maybe three from the actual perimeter. I have never entered the annex.”\n\n“Good.”\n\nMarcus looked at her.\n\n“You keep using that word when the information is bad.”\n\n“I use it when the information admits what it is.”\n\nA marked Metropolitan Police cruiser appeared ahead. It sat beside a line of temporary cones where officers were separating government vehicles from delivery traffic. A white electrical-service van had been pulled to the curb. One officer stood behind it reading the plate while another spoke into a shoulder radio.\n\nPCF-27 was four vehicles away.\n\nMarcus folded the map.\n\n“Garage entrance is right before the cones.”\n\nJulie saw the blue parking sign beneath an office tower. The ramp descended half a level before climbing inside the concrete structure. A camera housing faced every entering plate.\n\n“No clean entry,” Elias said.\n\n“There was never a clean entry.”\n\nThe electrical van’s driver stepped onto the sidewalk with both hands visible. The officer at the rear looked toward the moving traffic line.\n\nJulie turned into the garage.\n\nA ticket machine stood on the driver’s side beneath white fluorescent light. She lowered the window. Her right hand could not reach across her body without turning the wrist inside the brace.\n\nMarcus reached for the button.\n\n“No.”\n\n“You want to protect the integrity of the parking ticket?”\n\n“I want your hand on the case.”\n\nJulie leaned out and pressed the button with her left thumb. The machine clicked. A camera flashed above the plate. The paper ticket extended too far from her injured side. She caught it between two fingers and nearly dropped it before pulling it inside.\n\nThe barrier rose.\n\n“The camera has us,” Elias said.\n\n“It has the van entering at a known time,” Julie replied. “That record may matter later.”\n\nMarcus looked at the concrete ramp ahead. “You are choosing cameras now?”\n\n“I am choosing which facts they record.”\n\nThe digital clock changed to 07:22.\n\nJulie drove upward.\n\nEach level opened around rows of commuter cars and concrete columns striped with old paint. The lower floors were nearly full. On the fourth, two maintenance crews unloaded ladders from unmarked pickups. On the fifth, the eastern wall opened into broad rectangular bays.\n\nBeyond them, the federal district spread beneath pale morning light.\n\nHartwell did not announce itself with a sign visible from the garage. Traffic control did. Police motorcycles held the broad northern approach. Black vehicles passed through a temporary outer vehicle line and disappeared between federal buildings. To the east, a narrower lane ran behind a row of offices toward a controlled staff-and-service approach.\n\nThe principal motorcade entered from the north.\n\nThe support vehicle with the weak rear light was not with it.\n\nJulie continued to the sixth level.\n\nThe upper deck was less crowded. A delivery van occupied one corner. Three sedans stood beneath monthly-parking signs. The west exit ramp descended behind a concrete wall. The east spiral was visible through the center opening.\n\nTwo routes out.\n\nFor now.\n\nJulie parked PCF-27 nose-first toward the west ramp, close enough to the open east wall for Marcus to see the approaches without leaving the passenger seat. A concrete column hid most of the van from the garage’s internal aisle camera. It did not hide the plate image already stored at the entrance.\n\nShe shut off the engine.\n\nThe sudden quiet made their breathing audible.\n\nMarcus’s came shallow and controlled. Elias’s carried a faint catch when he shifted his injured hip. Julie’s pulse moved inside the wrist brace.\n\nShe looked at the dashboard clock.\n\n07:24:16.\n\n“Hard abort is seven-forty-two-thirty,” she said.\n\nMarcus turned toward her.\n\n“Conditions?”\n\n“We have continuous observation or a defensibly recoverable record of the suspected signer route. The module and board remain intact and with Elias. You retain the originals and a viable way out.”\n\n“And if one fails?”\n\n“We leave.”\n\n“If the challenge is one second from beginning?”\n\n“We leave.”\n\n“If the device appears while police are taking the ramp?”\n\n“We leave.”\n\nMarcus held her gaze.\n\n“You stayed eight seconds at Fenwick.”\n\n“I know.”\n\n“You told me the rule mattered most when success was close.”\n\n“I know.”\n\n“And then you let Elias change it.”\n\nElias looked up from the module. “I changed it.”\n\n“You both did.”\n\nJulie did not defend the seal. It had strengthened the evidence. It had also cost the primary exit and placed Bell, building security, Mercer, and a police officer inside a more dangerous extraction.\n\n“Seven-forty-two-thirty,” she said. “If the conditions do not pass, the operation ends.”\n\nMarcus waited.\n\n“Say the part you do not want to say.”\n\nJulie looked through the open wall toward Hartwell.\n\n“If the route is one step from proving Sterling held the device, and the conditions fail, we still leave.”\n\n“The device,” Elias said. “Not Sterling.”\n\nJulie turned to him. “Correct.”\n\nMarcus nodded once.\n\nThe rule existed outside her now.\n\nShe opened the driver’s door with her left hand.\n\nThe wind across the upper deck carried traffic noise and the intermittent chirp of reversing trucks. Julie crossed twenty feet to the open wall. Elias followed with the incident module held against his abdomen. His left leg shortened every third step. He used the concrete columns instead of Julie’s arm.\n\nMarcus remained in the van with the aluminum case, the recovery cartridge, the paper custody log, and the dead transponder.\n\nThe role cost him more than movement would have.\n\nJulie could see it in the way he watched them go.\n\nThey stopped behind a waist-high barrier at the east edge.\n\nFrom there, the outer Hartwell traffic divided into three visible streams.\n\nThe north approach carried the principal motorcade, marked security vehicles, and police control.\n\nA western curb held media vans and staff cars waiting beneath temporary restrictions.\n\nThe east lane carried deliveries, technical support, and office vehicles toward a covered checkpoint that sat outside the buildings hiding Hartwell’s secure interior.\n\nNone of the routes identified SSO-NS-004.\n\nElias leaned one shoulder against the concrete.\n\n“The local challenge can happen only after the device crosses into the briefing domain. Nothing here tells us where that boundary starts.”\n\n“Then we do not name it.”\n\nJulie studied the cameras instead.\n\nA traffic camera stood above the intersection feeding the east lane. A private loading-dock camera watched the same lane from the opposite building. The garage camera behind them covered the van, Marcus, and the opening where Julie and Elias stood.\n\nThree independent systems.\n\nDifferent owners.\n\nDifferent clocks.\n\nNot proof of what they saw.\n\nA record that could later test it.\n\n“Can the module make event markers without touching either partition?” Julie asked.\n\nElias looked at her.\n\n“The handling journal can record a local button event and device time.”\n\n“Does it change Partition A?”\n\n“No.”\n\n“Partition B?”\n\n“No. Both remain sealed. The journal belongs to the enclosure, not the evidence volumes.”\n\n“What does a marker prove?”\n\n“That someone pressed the control at a recorded time while the module was in this hardware state.”\n\n“Does it prove what we observed?”\n\n“No.”\n\n“Good.”\n\nHe gave her a tired look. “You are becoming predictable.”\n\n“Only in narrow areas.”\n\nElias used his left thumb to open the module’s handling screen. He kept his bandaged right index curled against the case.\n\nPARTITION A: SEALED / READ-ONLY / INTEGRITY VERIFIED  \nPARTITION B: SEALED / WSS-4 CONTROLLER SEAL PRESENT  \nDEVICE HANDLING JOURNAL: AVAILABLE\n\nHe selected EVENT MARK MODE.\n\nThe module displayed its internal clock.\n\n07:25:41.\n\nMarcus opened the paper custody log across the steering wheel. Julie spoke loudly enough for him to hear without leaving the van.\n\n“Record the observation position. Sixth level, east opening. Garage entry camera, internal aisle camera, municipal traffic camera above east intersection, private loading camera opposite the support lane.”\n\nHis pen moved.\n\nThe hand shook. The words remained legible.\n\n“What is the mission description?” he asked.\n\n“Observe the route. Do not identify a person.”\n\nHe wrote that too.\n\nFor the next ninety seconds, they watched ordinary vehicles.\n\nA food-service truck entered the east lane and stopped at a delivery barrier. The driver presented paperwork. A uniformed guard directed him toward a loading position.\n\nA gray government sedan arrived from the north and continued to the western staff curb.\n\nTwo black SUVs entered the principal approach and disappeared behind the outer motorcade line.\n\nNo weak rear light.\n\nNo portable signer.\n\nNo fact worth turning into one.\n\nAt 07:27:13, a police motorcycle left the north route and crossed toward the east lane.\n\nJulie raised one finger.\n\nElias pressed the event control.\n\nHANDLING EVENT 001  \nDEVICE TIME: 07:27:14.118  \nOPERATOR INPUT: MANUAL\n\nMarcus recorded the visible movement.\n\nThe motorcycle stopped at the eastern intersection and held cross traffic.\n\nA black sedan passed through.\n\nThen an empty staff shuttle.\n\nThen nothing.\n\nJulie watched the lane remain open.\n\n“They are preparing another arrival,” Marcus called from the van.\n\n“Or preserving a route.”\n\n“Same immediate decision.”\n\nThey kept watching.\n\nApex Building Three  \nReston, Virginia  \n07:28 Eastern Daylight Time\n\nThe plate hit reached Sarah Chen through Hartwell security, not Apex.\n\nA commercial-garage camera had captured PCF-27 at 07:21:52. The plate system compared it against the District lookout two minutes later. Hartwell’s temporary perimeter desk received the alert because the garage sat inside its traffic-control zone. Metropolitan Police opened the image to verify the vehicle before forwarding it to the joint incident channel.\n\nSeparate systems.\n\nA visible delay.\n\nA record of who acted when.\n\nSarah enlarged the garage map. Two vehicle exits. Four pedestrian stairs. Seven levels occupied by office workers, contractors, and morning commuters.\n\nArthur Vance’s executive channel opened beside it.\n\n“Direct Mercer to recover the media before Hartwell admits the signer.”\n\nSarah looked at the words.\n\nHe had not asked whether Julie was in the garage.\n\nHe had not asked whether the signer was there.\n\nHe had placed the material and the Hartwell event inside one sentence.\n\nShe marked the time in her incident file.\n\nDaniel Mercer answered over vehicle noise.\n\n“We are six minutes out. District units are closer.”\n\n“Hartwell security controls the federal perimeter,” Sarah said. “Metropolitan Police controls the public garage. You do not enter the annex security zone without invitation.”\n\n“Understood.”\n\n“Garage is occupied. No ballistic force absent an identified deadly threat and clear background. Preserve life, subjects, and evidence.”\n\nVance cut into the channel.\n\n“Telemetry recovery remains the priority.”\n\nMercer waited for Sarah.\n\n“Capture all three if present,” she said. “Separate them. Secure the case and any electronic media under documented custody. Do not destroy or disconnect anything.”\n\n“Receiving authority?”\n\n“Metropolitan Police until a federal lead is named.”\n\nIt was not the answer Vance wanted.\n\nIt was an answer Mercer could put on a receipt.\n\nSarah transmitted the vehicle image, the garage plan, and the two exits. She did not warn Julie. She assigned units to the public ramps and pedestrian stairs and asked Hartwell security to preserve its outer-camera records.\n\nThe request was denied pending federal review.\n\nThe denial entered her incident file anyway.\n\nOn the garage image, PCF-27 climbed out of camera view.\n\nJulie had not escaped observation.\n\nShe had moved to where every institution would have to explain what it saw.\n\nCommercial Garage West of Hartwell  \n07:31 Eastern Daylight Time\n\nThe support vehicle returned from the south.\n\nJulie saw the weak left rear light before she saw the rest of it.\n\nThe black SUV entered the cross street one block below the garage and stopped behind the police motorcycle. It had no flags and no visible emergency lights. Its windows were dark. A second vehicle followed, a smaller black sedan that had not been part of the motorcade at the earlier intersection.\n\n“Same SUV,” Marcus said.\n\n“What makes it the same?” Julie asked.\n\n“Left rear running light. Same roof rack. Same three-inch gap between the rear bumper and the receiver cover.”\n\nElias looked at him.\n\n“You saw that while bleeding through your collar?”\n\n“I saw vehicles for twenty-seven years.”\n\nJulie studied the SUV.\n\nThe running light was enough to distinguish it from the two black vehicles already inside the principal approach. The roof rack and receiver cover strengthened the observation. They did not identify its occupants or purpose.\n\n“Record as probable same vehicle,” she said. “Not confirmed.”\n\nMarcus wrote.\n\nElias pressed the marker.\n\nHANDLING EVENT 002  \nDEVICE TIME: 07:31:22.604  \nOPERATOR INPUT: MANUAL\n\nThe motorcycle released the lane.\n\nThe SUV moved east.\n\nThe sedan followed.\n\nNeither entered the principal motorcade approach.\n\nThey turned into the staff-and-support lane.\n\nJulie felt the objective change.\n\nThey were no longer searching every route.\n\nThey had one physical stream connected to Sterling’s motorcade and separated from his public arrival.\n\nThat did not make it the signer stream.\n\nIt made it the first route worth preserving.\n\n“Continuous from here,” she said.\n\nMarcus checked the mirrors inside the garage.\n\n“No police on this level.”\n\n“Ramps?”\n\n“Clear.”\n\n“Case?”\n\n“Green. Latches closed.”\n\n“Folder?”\n\n“With me.”\n\n“Module?”\n\nElias turned the display toward her without opening the partitions.\n\nBoth seals remained.\n\n“Board?”\n\nHe pressed the padded sleeve beneath his shirt.\n\n“In custody.”\n\nJulie looked back toward the east lane.\n\nThe black SUV stopped at an outer holding position before the covered checkpoint. A uniformed officer approached the driver’s window. The sedan remained one vehicle length behind.\n\nNothing happened for twenty seconds.\n\nThen the officer pointed the sedan toward a western staff curb.\n\nThe SUV stayed.\n\nThe stream split.\n\n“Sedan is not our vehicle,” Marcus said.\n\n“Not unless something transfers.”\n\nThe sedan moved away.\n\nNo door opened.\n\nNo object changed hands.\n\nJulie kept the line on the SUV.\n\nAt 07:33:08, a white building-services truck entered the lane from the opposite direction and stopped between the garage and the holding position.\n\nThe truck blocked Julie’s view completely.\n\nShe shifted left.\n\nConcrete closed the angle.\n\nShe moved right.\n\nThe garage column took the SUV away.\n\n“Lost visual,” she said.\n\nElias looked at the module.\n\n“Marker?”\n\n“Yes.”\n\nHe pressed it.\n\nHANDLING EVENT 003  \nDEVICE TIME: 07:33:11.093  \nOPERATOR INPUT: MANUAL\n\nMarcus wrote the obstruction time.\n\nJulie looked at the cameras.\n\nThe municipal camera above the intersection still faced the SUV’s approach. The private loading camera across the lane looked past the service truck from the opposite direction.\n\nTheir own eyes had lost the vehicle.\n\nThe external record had not necessarily lost it.\n\n“Recoverable observation continues through two independent cameras,” she said.\n\n“Assuming they preserve it,” Marcus replied.\n\n“Record the assumption.”\n\nHe did.\n\nThe service truck reversed into a loading position. Its rear cleared the holding lane at 07:33:29.\n\nThe SUV remained where it had been.\n\nNo one had entered the checkpoint.\n\nJulie exhaled once.\n\n“Direct visual restored.”\n\nElias marked it.\n\nBelow them, a siren entered the garage and stopped.\n\nMarcus turned the service radio higher.\n\n“Unit Three at commercial garage west. Suspect plate confirmed. Establishing east vehicle exit. Additional units approach west. Garage management reports upper-level access open.”\n\n“They found the garage,” Elias said.\n\n“We expected them to.”\n\n“You did not tell me how much expectation was supposed to help.”\n\n“It keeps surprise from making the decision.”\n\nJulie checked the time.\n\n07:34:02.\n\nEight minutes and twenty-eight seconds to the hard abort.\n\nA Metropolitan Police cruiser appeared on the east spiral two levels below. Its lights remained off. The driver moved slowly among civilian vehicles.\n\nNo tactical rush.\n\nNo gunfire.\n\nAn honest search becoming physically real.\n\n"